<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Hardened-runtime entitlements for the notarized macOS build (FN-OCR-13-03).

  Apple notarization REQUIRES the hardened runtime. Tauri 2 enables the
  hardened runtime automatically when it signs with a Developer ID identity
  (i.e. when APPLE_SIGNING_IDENTITY / APPLE_CERTIFICATE are present in CI) and
  applies these entitlements via `bundle.macOS.entitlements` in tauri.conf.json.

  The three keys below are the standard set a WKWebView-backed app needs to run
  under the hardened runtime — WebKit's JavaScript engine maps writable+
  executable memory (JIT). Without them a notarized build can launch and then
  crash on first page load. They are all on Apple's allowlist, so they do NOT
  block notarization.

  If a future audit wants the tightest possible surface, the two memory keys can
  be trimmed and re-tested on a clean machine; disable-library-validation is only
  needed if we ever load unsigned third-party dylibs. Left in for now because the
  cost is low and the failure mode (silent crash on a pilot's machine) is high.

  When the build runs WITHOUT signing secrets (ad-hoc / unsigned dev release),
  these entitlements are simply applied during the ad-hoc codesign and are inert.
-->
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN"
  "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
  <dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
  </dict>
</plist>
